@node "Requirements" "ED/GED | Requirements"
This program requires OS2.04 or higher. It does ofcourse also need a  copy of
GoldED  to  run.  The current version will probably only work with GoldED 2.0,
due to the new pref handeling scheeme of GoldED.
@endnode

@node "Installation" "ED/GED | Installation & SetUp"
This  is  SO  simple!  Just  replace   your   current   GoldED   quickstarter
(called either  ED  or GED). If you don't know how to do this, it's a miracle
that you know how to work GoldED :-)

Also copy "LoadConfig.ged" into the GoldED:Arexx/ drawer.
@endnode

@node "Usage" "ED/GED | Usage"
 @{b}The GoldED quickstart-replacement:@{ub}

The template is  no  longer  exactly  the  same  as  for  the  original  GoldEd
quickstarter, but for compability reasons, it still supports the same arguments
as for the original quickstarter.

The template is now:

F=FILES/M,C=CONFIG/K,S=SCREEN/K,HIDE/S,-STICKY/S,Y=STICKY/S,L=LINE/N,...
...I=IGNOREENV/S,F=FORCEPREF/S

Heres a more specific explanation to the template:

(Please note, that English is not my native language, eg. some explanations may
or may not be difficult to understand - sorry!)

F=FILES/M:  Here you can specify all the files you want opened.  All filenames
            can contain wildcards. If a file contains a wildcard and there's no
            matches for this wildcard - no file will be opened and  the GoldED
            screen  will be brought to the front. No error will be returned. If
            the file does not exist and  the  filename  does  not  contain any
            wildcard, a new window will be opened with the specified name.

C=CONFIG/K: Here you can change the configuration at  any  time.  Please note,
            that changing the configuration will take a few seconds, especially
            if your system is not too fast.

S=SCREEN/K: Changes the public screen where GoldED has it's windows opened. Can
            be changed at any time!

HIDE/S:     Only works when starting GoldED the first time.  Just  makes sure,
            that GoldED is resident, but no windows is opened.

-STICKY/S:  Will prevent the quick-starter from returning, until the window is
            closed.  When  opening  more  than one file in sticky mode, it will
            only create the lock on the last window opened. If the last window
            opened is the first one closed, the quick-starter returns control.

Y=STICKY/S: Same function as -STICKY (For compability)

L=LINE/N:   Jumps to the specified line in a file. When opening more  that one
            file,  it  will  only  jump to the line in the last file opened. (I
            will change this, if anyone asks me!).

The difference between the original quickstarter and this version, is that this
one will recognize the fileextension (eg. "c" in ged.c) and then it will try to
load the configuration that is appropiate for this kind of file. This  requires
a  specific  file  name  to  be  used  in  your  "GoldED:config/"  drawer.  The
configuration file must be named with the same name as the extension  with  the
".prefs"  added  to the name. For a "c" file, the pref file is called "c.prefs"
and for a "tex" file "tex.prefs".

To be able to use the above mentioned feature, you have to set the  environment
variable "GED_AUTOCFG". This can be done as follows:

    setenv GED_AUTOCFG 0

(Press this @{"button" system "setenv GED_AUTOCFG 0"} to set the variable now.)

The contents is not important - the program just checks if the variable  exists
or not.

Here are the two new options:

I=IGNOREENV/S:
            This ignores if "GoldED/GED_AUTOCFG" is set  or  not.  This means,
            that  there  will be no checking of the extension, eg. no change of
            prefs.

F=FORCEPREF/S:
            Forces  GoldED  to  load  the  pref  file  according  to  the file
            extension, even if this is the current configuration.

@{b}LoadConfig.ged:@{ub}

This arexx macro can either be installed as a seperate menu entry or you  could
place  it  into  the  open  menus,  thus  loading  the appropiate configuration
everytime you open a file. Check out GoldED.guide to see how to install menus.
@endnode

@node "About" "ED/GED | About SA Development"
About SA-Productions:

We're two  university  students  (Anders  Hybertz  and  Sĝren  Berg Glasius) 
who like to program in our spare time. We create all sorts of small utilities
that we need and that we think that others may need too. Some  of  them  goes
out in the public domain (as MailWare) and others we just keep to ourself. We
both studdy computer science and electronics at  the  University  of  Odense,
Denmark.

Program status:

The program is MailWare, this means, that if you use try  this  program,  and
even  if  you don't like it, you must send the author an email or a postcard.
Please think about the fact, that we have put some hours into  this  project,
and have  used  time to distribute it onto the net. It would be very nice to
know, where it ended up! If you like the program, please let us know! If  you
didn't like it, or if it had some bugs, that made you throw it out, then tell us
too! We can not make changes to a program, if we don't know  where  people want
the changes! Also we can not fix the bugs (others than the ones we find our
self) if you don't tell us, where they are and what they do.

Think about it - but do more than that: Send that e-mail or that postcard, it no
efford at all, but it will make us happy to know, that others but our self is
using our program.

